A go -slow by metered taxis drivers has brought traffic to a standstill on the R24 in Edenvale towards OR Tambo International Airport on Friday. It is believed that the drivers are calling for Uber taxis to be regulated.Acting National Police Commissioner Khomotso Phahlane says the march is illegal and harsh measures will be taken against those who are found to be on the wrong side of the law.&#8220;The metered taxi drivers decided to copy the truck strike that happened last week, the operation will result in in some taxis which are being parked on the road to be impounded, we cannot allow lawlessness.&#8221; he said.JHB &#8211; R21 South, Metered Taxi Drive Protest: RAMP CLOSURE: no access to R24 West (i.e. towards Gilloolys and JHB) Rob Byrne (@TrafficSA) March 10, 2017Ekhuruleni Metro Police spokesperson Kobeli Mokheseng says it not clear what the demonstrations are about but police are on the scene negotiating with the drivers.JHB &#8211; R21 South: Metered Taxi Drive Protest: between Tembisa and the Airport &#8211; DELAYS all the way through https://t.co/ymNDwAeJ9j Rob Byrne (@TrafficSA) March 10, 2017Motorists are advised to use alternative routes to avoid delays.JHB &#8211; R24 East: Metered Taxi Driver Protest: RT @eloosif Situation at Barbara Road right now @TrafficSA @ortambo_int pic.twitter.com/DQ2686GkpC Rob Byrne (@TrafficSA) March 10, 2017&nbsp;More to follow as the story develops.